column17:
Variable-sized array is supported by most of the modern C++ compiler, but it is not recommended. In addition, you cannot initialize the variable-size array like your code. You need to use a loop.

Here is a modified example to illustrate why using variable-sized array is a bad idea.

The program looks good when n is small. But when n is large, your program crashes (it is a runtime error, not a compilation error). Even worse, you basically don't know the minimum value n that causes the runtime error. In other words, your program may suddenly crash.

If possible, always create a fixed size array (if you know the size of the array, and the size is quite small), or use dynamic allocation (it is possible to handle the failure by using exception handling technique).

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
void foo(int n) {
int bar[n]; // a modern C++ compiler supports that
int i;
for (i=0; i<n; i++)
bar[i] = 0; 
for (i=0; i<n; i++)
cout << bar[i] << " ";
cout << endl;
}
int main() {
foo(10); // it is usually okay for a small number n
foo(10000000); // runtime error! Not a compilation error.
return 0;
}

