This means that in your updateMapForMoveAction() function, not all possible paths have a return value. E.g., if you have a function int modulo3(int)

int modulo3(int num) {
if (num % 3 == 0) return 0;
else if (num % 3 == 1) return 1;
else if (num % 3 == 2) return 2;
// The compiler may think it's possible for your program to reach here.
}

Although you know that this has covered all the possible cases of num (does it?), the compiler may not be smart enough to understand it. The only thing it knows is that your if doesn't have an else part and it thinks that it's possible that it reaches the end of the if block and exit the function without returning.

Then the compiler may throw warnings at you for not returning in a non-void function.

Usually as good practice, it is encouraged to return in every return path even if you think some path is impossible to reach since it's easier to debug this way.

Why? For the above example, what if the input num is negative? In C++11, negative modulo positive gives negative number. Then your compound if block will not be able to catch that case. This kind of bugs can be insidious at times.

If you do not always return, the function can return indeterministic value (actually its UB, meaning your program can crash), which is usually very hard to debug since the output may be different every time, causing inconsistent behavior.

However, if you always return, say return some placeholder value (e.g. -1) for return paths that is "impossible to reach", it's easier to debug since you will know there is something unexpected happening in that function. Consistently incorrect behaviour is better than inconsistent behaviour (undefined behavior).
Of course, there are better ways to do this (via exception). :)

